##Lung atrophied into dried bean curd after lung transplantation

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

By Hu Danping, thepaper.cn

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The operation was performed in a negative-pressure operating room at infectious diseases hospital in Wuxi

Professor Chen Jingyu, a famous lung transplant expert and "the first lung transplant recipient in China" , successfully performed the world's first double lung transplant in Wuxi, Jiangsu Province, on Feb. 29.

In an interview with The Paper news (www.thepaper.cn ) on March 1, Chen Jingyu said that the lung function of the patient with new coronavirus pneumonia had been seriously impaired, he and his team took a big risk in performing such an exploratory operation in order to give more critically ill patients with new pneumonia and dying patients a chance at life.

Dialogue with Chen Jingyu

The paper: Please tell us about the patient who underwent the lung transplant.

Chen Jingyu: The new case of pneumonia in Jiangsu province, Male, 59 years old, onset on January 23, confirmed on January 26 Covid-19, tracheal intubation on February 7, ECMO on February 22, transferred to Wuxi Infectious Disease Hospital on February 24, after endotracheal intubation, ECMO and medication, continuous nucleic acid testing was negative, but both lung functions were severely impaired and irreversible.

What are the medical indications for lung transplantation in patients with new coronary pneumonia? What was the pre-operative condition of the first patient with a new pneumonia lung transplant?

Chen Jingyu: First, the patient is maintained by breathing and ECMO, the double lung failure is irreversible; second, the nucleic acid test is negative for many times continuously; third, the other organs function is basically normal, the whole body condition can withstand lung transplantation.

Before the lung transplant, the patient had been kept alive by breathing and ECMO, but his lungs were in advanced stages, fibrotic and shrunken to a dried bean curd, that's why we had the lung transplant.

In another case, on February 28th, the patient suffered from a right sided lung hemorrhage, estimated at 2,500 ml. The patient suffered from hemorrhagic shock and was on the verge of death. On the 29th, the patient was lucky enough to wait until a brain dead patient in the province donated his lung to charity, so our team can take a shot.

The paper: You mentioned the need for a lung transplant to be negative for multiple consecutive nucleic acid tests. Why? How many nucleic acid tests were performed on this first lung transplant patient with new coronary pneumonia?

Chen Jingyu: This patient underwent surgery for five consecutive days after the nucleic acid test was negative.

The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus which is highly contagious. There's not enough research or understanding of the virus. But it is now clear that a positive nucleic acid test for the new coronavirus means the virus is still active in the body.

So in order to perform this surgery, from the point of view of medical staff safety, we hope that the patient is not contagious, it is better to test negative for nucleic acid for several days in a row, so that it is relatively safe.

But a negative nucleic acid test can not rule out that there is no virus in the lungs that have to be removed, so we need to be very careful when we operate to make sure that there is no infection in the staff.

The paper: What are the differences and similarities between lung transplantation in patients with new coronary pneumonia and those who need lung transplantation due to other diseases? Will it be harder to recover?

Chen Jingyu: this patient's lung transplant after the recovery of the road is certainly longer than other patients with ordinary pulmonary fibrosis, because he suffered too much early, his immune function is very low, recovery time is certainly longer than others. And there may be other accidents we do not know, so this surgery is an exploratory surgery.

The paper: Why such an exploratory operation?

Chen Jingyu: Because the death rate of the new severe pneumonia patients is too high. Currently equipped with breathing machine plus ECMO patients with low success rate. Our team is taking a huge risk doing this surgery, which is actually giving life to critically ill patients and dying patients.

We also hope that we can gain some experience from this case, just like doing an autopsy. Compared to an autopsy, I think it makes more sense, because an autopsy is something that the patient sees after death, and we're not only trying to save the patient's life, but we're also trying to get a sense of the disease from his lungs.

We have seen data released today by the Hubei Health Commission showing that there were 7,107 severe cases of new coronary pneumonia in Hubei Province on February 29. If the lung transplant is effective, you, as a doctor, are also the member of the National People's Congress, what are the recommendations for the treatment of critically ill patients in Hubei?

Chen Jingyu: If we can succeed in the next stage, I will suggest that the National Health Commission organize a team for lung transplantation in patients with new pneumonia, to select suitable lung transplant recipients for the critically ill patients in Wuhan, the success rate is high, younger patients, such as the thirty, 40-50-year-old young critically ill patients with new pneumonia for lung transplant treatment.

The paper: When do you mean when will the relevant authorities be advised after the lung transplantation is successful? What's the status of the transplant patient so far?

Chen Jingyu: At present, the patient's condition is stable. Success, I mean, depends on the patient's breathing machine and Ecmo being completely evacuated, and the patient's initial success is when he can carry out rehabilitation exercises. It's going to be a couple of days until I can take it down, and then I'll have a prediction.

What is the risk of lung transplantation for patients with NCP for medical staff who perform the surgery? What were the difficulties encountered during the operation on the first patient?

Chen Jingyu: The risk is very high. I don't know if there is any residual virus in the patient's lungs. Whether the virus is active or infectious, so we have to do this surgery under a full set of protective conditions. It's very stressful for the doctors.

It is also more difficult in operation. It is not easy to talk between teams, and there is no eye contact. Basically, everyone is sweating all over. After five or six hours, we can only rely on the close cooperation of the team and a tacit understanding that everyone has reached with each other for a long time, to get this surgery done.

Because we have performed more than 1,000 lung transplants, this operation is usually a routine operation. We usually do one lung transplant in two or three days, the whole team is already very well-coordinated. So for us, it wasn't a particularly long surgery, it was basically a very quick procedure.
